I think it's important to stress the difference between hardness and immutability. I think it's something that everyone misses. People are too hellbent on "deploy once and never change" and believe everything outside of this is just "not blockchain".

For most folks I think the concept is still too nebulous. "Blockchain is about stuff that doesn't change, muh bitcoins". It'd be interesting to showcase examples of hardness, and the "spectrum of hardness". An unupgradeable ERC20 is "super hard" and the ERC20r standard (https://arxiv.org/abs/2208.00543) is "less hard"

Would love to have your take on 
- how hardness relates to governance. 
- how this framework helps better understand where blockchain technology can be applied

On the last point: imo where the hardness options aren't great, but not where there's already one. For example tokenizing real estate will create a competing hardness standard, likely to fail. But NFTs created a hardness standard where there was basically none (was impossible to sell jpegs in the current art market)
